She said that despite Kenya having many skilled lawyers, access to justice for many Kenyans remained mirage because the “attitude of law students and lawyers limit their focus to the rich as they ignore the needy.”
She said the Sustainable Development Goal number 16 seeks to promote the rule of law at national and international levels besides ensuring justice for all.
Access to justice





“Article 48 of our Constitution exhorts the State to ensure access to justice to all persons. It also recognises that access to justice can be hindered by distance and cost and every cost we charge should be minimum and should not impede access to justice,” said Prof Kameri
She observed that access to justice requires many actors to reach the poor.  
“If justice is going to be attained, legal aid must be provided to all,” she said.
She called for improved practical lessons to all law students to prepare them well for the task ahead.   
She observed that universities and other legal education providers have a role to play and appealed to lawyers to give back to the society by facilitating democratic governance, and the rule of law.
 “Legal education must serve the needs of the whole society and not just the rich. Law schools and other legal education providers must integrate legal aid into their curriculum,” said Prof Kameri.



